VALUES
(19, 136, 13, 13, 'kjv', 'To him which divided the Red sea into parts: for his mercy endureth for ever:', 0, 77, 'connection', 'Red Sea Crossings', 'This verse echoes the miraculous event of the Israelites'' escape from Egypt. It can be cross-referenced with Exodus 14:21-22, which describes the actual division of the sea, demonstrating God''s power and mercy. Additionally, Hebrews 11:29 mentions this event as a demonstration of faith, highlighting how pivotal this moment is in the narrative of Israel''s salvation.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Exodus 14:21-22", "description": "Describes the crossing of the Red Sea."}, {"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Hebrews 11:29", "description": "Comments on the faith involved in this event."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 13, 13, 'kjv', 'divided the Red sea into parts', 13, 43, 'greek', 'Significance of ''Divided''', 'The Hebrew term for ''divided'' is גָּזַר (gazar, H1504), meaning to cut or separate. This signifies not only a physical act of parting the waters but also represents God''s decisive intervention in history, allowing for deliverance and salvation. This action showcases His authority over creation.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H1504", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew term."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 13, 13, 'kjv', 'for his mercy endureth for ever:', 45, 77, 'theology', 'God''s Enduring Mercy', 'This refrain emphasizes God''s unchanging nature and covenant love. Many scholars believe it reflects the core of Israel''s understanding of divine mercy, which is rooted in God''s faithfulness to His promises. This concept is foundational to the theology of the Old Testament, affirming that God''s mercy is not only a characteristic but a covenantal assurance for His people.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Psalms Commentary", "description": "Discusses the theological implications of God''s mercy."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 13, 13, 'kjv', 'divided the Red sea into parts:', 13, 44, 'question', 'Reflection on Divine Intervention', 'What does the act of God dividing the Red Sea reveal about His ability to intervene in seemingly impossible situations in our lives? How can we trust in His mercy during our own ''Red Sea'' moments?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 14, 14, 'kjv', 'And made Israel to pass through the midst of it: for his mercy endureth for ever:', 0, 81, 'connection', 'Red Sea Crossing', 'This verse connects with Exodus 14:22, which describes God parting the Red Sea, allowing Israel to escape from Egypt. This event not only illustrates God''s power but also His faithfulness to His covenant people. The repeated phrase ''for his mercy endureth for ever'' underscores the theological belief that God''s mercy is a consistent theme throughout Israel''s history.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Exodus 14:22", "description": "Describes the miraculous crossing of the Red Sea."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 14, 14, 'kjv', 'made Israel to pass through', 4, 31, 'greek', 'Key Action: ''Pass Through''', 'Hebrew: עָבַר (avar, H5674) - to pass over, to cross. This term emphasizes not only the physical act of crossing the Red Sea but also the spiritual transition from slavery to freedom. It signifies God''s intervention in human history to deliver His people, highlighting His role as a liberator.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H5674", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew word used."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 14, 14, 'kjv', 'for his mercy endureth for ever', 49, 80, 'theology', 'God''s Enduring Mercy', 'Many scholars believe this refrain emphasizes the unchanging nature of God''s mercy throughout history. Theologically, it suggests that God''s actions toward His people are rooted in His covenant love, illustrating that His mercy is not merely a one-time act but a continual characteristic of His divine nature.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discusses God''s merciful nature in the context of Israel''s history."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 14, 14, 'kjv', 'made Israel to pass through', 4, 31, 'question', 'Reflecting on Deliverance', 'What does it mean for you personally to recognize that God actively made a way for His people to escape bondage? How does this understanding of divine intervention influence your faith journey today?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 15, 15, 'kjv', 'overthrew Pharaoh and his host in the Red sea', 4, 49, 'connection', 'Historical Deliverance', 'This phrase highlights God''s decisive victory over Pharaoh and his army, which parallels Exodus 14:27-28 where God commands Moses to stretch his hand over the sea, causing it to return to its normal state, leading to Pharaoh''s downfall. This connection emphasizes God''s power to deliver His people from oppression and serves as a foundational event in the history of Israel''s liberation.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Exodus 14:27-28", "description": "Describes God''s actions leading to Pharaoh''s destruction."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 15, 15, 'kjv', 'for his mercy endureth for ever', 51, 82, 'theology', 'Nature of God''s Mercy', 'The repeated refrain of God''s mercy enduring forever throughout Psalm 136 suggests a key theological assertion about God''s character. Many scholars believe this reflects the unchanging, steadfast nature of divine love and faithfulness, which contrasts human frailty. This enduring mercy is foundational to understanding God''s covenant relationship with His people, reminding believers of His continual grace amid judgment.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discusses the significance of God''s enduring mercy."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 15, 15, 'kjv', 'overthrew Pharaoh and his host in the Red sea', 4, 49, 'question', 'Understanding Divine Justice', 'What does the overthrow of Pharaoh signify about God''s justice versus human rebellion? Considering Pharaoh''s hardened heart, how does this event illustrate the consequences of defying God''s will? Reflecting on this can deepen our understanding of divine authority and the seriousness of our response to God''s guidance.', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 16, 16, 'kjv', 'To him which led his people through the wilderness: for his mercy endureth for ever.', 0, 84, 'connection', 'Wilderness Journey', 'This verse connects to Exodus 13:21, where it describes the Lord leading the Israelites through the wilderness with a pillar of cloud by day and a pillar of fire by night. It reflects God''s active guidance during their journey, emphasizing His continual presence and the significance of divine leadership in times of uncertainty. The repeated refrain of His mercy enduring forever highlights the nature of God''s commitment to His people.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Exodus 13:21", "description": "The Lord''s guidance of Israel through the wilderness."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 16, 16, 'kjv', 'which led his people', 7, 27, 'theology', 'Divine Guidance', 'This phrase suggests a key theological concept of God as a shepherd leading His people, akin to Psalm 23:1, ''The Lord is my shepherd; I shall not want.'' Many scholars believe this imagery emphasizes God’s protective and guiding role throughout the journey of life, symbolizing His provision and care, particularly in challenging circumstances.', 'person.2.fill', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Psalms 23:1", "description": "Explores God''s role as shepherd."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 16, 16, 'kjv', 'for his mercy endureth for ever.', 52, 84, 'question', 'Understanding God''s Mercy', 'What does it mean for God''s mercy to endure forever in the context of our own spiritual journeys? How can we respond to His enduring mercy in our lives, especially when facing trials or uncertainties, similar to the Israelites in the wilderness?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 16, 16, 'kjv', 'led his people through the wilderness', 13, 50, 'greek', 'Hebrew Terms for Leadership', 'יָרַד (yarad, H3381) - to lead down, descend. This term underscores God''s action in leading His people, not just physically, but spiritually and morally, through the trials of the wilderness experience.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H3381", "description": "Strong''s Hebrew number for ''to lead down''."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 17, 17, 'kjv', 'To him which smote great kings:', 0, 31, 'connection', 'Divine Judgment References', 'This phrase connects with Joshua 10:24-26, where God delivers the enemies of Israel into Joshua''s hands, demonstrating His sovereignty over nations. The theme of God striking down great kings is consistent throughout Scripture, affirming His ultimate authority in both judgment and deliverance.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Joshua 10:24-26", "description": "God''s deliverance of Israel and judgment on their enemies"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 17, 17, 'kjv', 'which smote great kings:', 7, 31, 'greek', 'Understanding ''smote''', 'נָכָה (nakah, H5221) - to strike, beat, or kill. This term conveys a sense of decisive action by God against formidable opponents, emphasizing His power and the seriousness of His judgment against those who oppose His people.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H5221", "description": "Hebrew word for ''smote''"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 17, 17, 'kjv', 'for his mercy endureth for ever:', 32, 64, 'theology', 'Mercy and Judgment', 'This repetition of God''s mercy following His acts of judgment suggests a theological principle that God''s mercy is foundational to His character. Many scholars believe this reflects the balance between His justice and grace, illustrating that while God does judge nations, His ultimate desire is for restoration and mercy.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discussion on God''s mercy and justice"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 17, 17, 'kjv', 'To him which smote great kings:', 0, 31, 'question', 'Reflecting on God''s Power', 'What does it mean for us today that God has the power to defeat great kings? How should this knowledge affect our trust in Him during times of personal or communal challenges?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 18, 18, 'kjv', 'And slew famous kings: for his mercy endureth for ever:', 0, 55, 'connection', 'Cross-Reference to Kings', 'The mention of God slaying famous kings brings to mind Numbers 21:32-35, where Israel defeats Sihon and Og, kings of the Amorites and Bashan, respectively. This connection emphasizes God''s sovereignty and power in delivering His people, reinforcing the theme of divine mercy and intervention throughout Israel''s history.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Numbers 21:32-35", "description": "Describes the defeat of Sihon and Og, illustrating God''s might."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 18, 18, 'kjv', 'famous kings', 9, 21, 'theology', 'God''s Sovereignty Over Leaders', 'This phrase highlights God''s authority over earthly powers. Many scholars believe that the mention of ''famous kings'' serves to illustrate that no matter how powerful or renowned, human rulers are ultimately subject to God''s will. This teaches believers about the transient nature of earthly authority compared to God''s everlasting sovereignty.', 'person.2.fill', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discusses the implications of God''s authority over nations and rulers."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 18, 18, 'kjv', 'for his mercy endureth for ever:', 23, 55, 'question', 'Understanding God''s Mercy', 'What does it mean for God''s mercy to endure forever in the context of His judgment over kings? How does this eternal mercy influence your understanding of justice and grace in your own life and in the world today?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 18, 18, 'kjv', 'And slew famous kings:', 0, 22, 'greek', 'Key Hebrew Term', 'מָשַׁח (mashach, H4886) - to smear, anoint, or slay. The use of this term indicates not only the act of killing but suggests a divine appointment in the removal of these kings, aligning with the theological notion of God''s providential governance.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H4886", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew term related to slaying."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 19, 19, 'kjv', 'Sihon king of the Amorites: for his mercy endureth for ever:', 0, 60, 'connection', 'Historical Context of Sihon', 'The mention of Sihon, king of the Amorites, connects to Numbers 21:23-24, where Israel defeats him in battle. This victory is significant as it represents God''s faithfulness in fulfilling His promises to Israel. The recurring theme of God''s mercy enduring forever emphasizes that His grace extends even in moments of judgment, showcasing His character as both just and merciful.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Numbers 21:23-24", "description": "Israel''s confrontation with Sihon and the victory granted by God."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 19, 19, 'kjv', 'Sihon king of the Amorites:', 0, 27, 'theology', 'God''s Sovereignty in Conquest', 'This verse illustrates the theological concept of divine sovereignty over nations. Many scholars believe that God''s selection of Israel to conquer the land of Sihon reflects His overarching plan for redemption and the establishment of His covenant people. It emphasizes that God orchestrates historical events to fulfill His purposes, reinforcing the belief in His control over earthly kingdoms.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Insights on God''s sovereignty and historical events in the Old Testament."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 19, 19, 'kjv', 'for his mercy endureth for ever:', 28, 60, 'question', 'Understanding Divine Mercy', 'What does it mean for God''s mercy to endure forever, especially in the context of judgment against Sihon? How does this aspect of God''s character encourage you to view difficult situations in your own life? Reflecting on God''s enduring mercy can reshape our understanding of grace and justice.', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 19, 19, 'kjv', 'for his mercy endureth for ever:', 28, 60, 'greek', 'Enduring Mercy in Hebrew', 'חֶסֶד (chesed, H2617) - steadfast love, mercy, kindness. This term conveys a deep sense of loyalty and faithfulness, representing God''s unwavering commitment to His covenant people. It underlines the profound nature of God’s mercy that transcends time and circumstance, making it a central theme in the Psalms.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H2617", "description": "Strong''s definition of ''chesed'' emphasizing God''s lovingkindness."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 20, 20, 'kjv', 'Og the king of Bashan', 4, 25, 'connection', 'Cross-Reference to Deuteronomy', 'Og, king of Bashan, is mentioned in Deuteronomy 3:11, where his formidable size and strength are highlighted. This connection emphasizes God''s power in defeating even the mightiest foes, showcasing His sovereignty over nations. Understanding Og''s defeat helps illustrate the broader theme of God''s faithfulness in giving Israel victory and land.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Deuteronomy 3:11", "description": "Og was notable for his size and strength, enhancing the context of God''s mercy and power."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 20, 20, 'kjv', 'for his mercy endureth for ever', 27, 58, 'theology', 'Enduring Mercy of God', 'This phrase underscores a central theme in biblical theology: the everlasting nature of God''s mercy. Many scholars believe this reflects the covenantal love that God has for His people, assuring them of His support despite their failures. This enduring mercy invites believers to trust in God''s faithfulness through all circumstances.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 20, 20, 'kjv', 'Og the king of Bashan', 4, 25, 'question', 'Reflection on God''s Sovereignty', 'In considering the defeat of Og, how does this event demonstrate God''s control over powerful adversaries in your life? What does it mean for you personally to acknowledge God''s sovereignty in your challenges?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 20, 20, 'kjv', 'for his mercy endureth for ever', 27, 58, 'greek', 'Hebrew Term for Mercy', 'חֶסֶד (chesed, H2617) - mercy, loving-kindness. This term conveys a deep, loyal love and unconditional kindness, foundational to understanding God''s relationship with His people. Its repetition throughout this psalm emphasizes the reliability of God''s character.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H2617", "description": "Indicates the Hebrew term for mercy used in the context of God''s enduring love."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 21, 21, 'kjv', 'And gave their land for an heritage: for his mercy endureth for ever:', 0, 69, 'connection', 'Land as Divine Gift', 'This phrase connects with Deuteronomy 9:4-5, where God instructs Israel not to claim the land due to their righteousness, but because of His promise to their ancestors. This emphasizes that the land was a gift from God, reinforcing the theme of divine mercy and grace in the allocation of heritage.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Deuteronomy 9:4-5", "description": "God reminds Israel that the land is given not because of their merit."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 21, 21, 'kjv', 'And gave their land for an heritage: for his mercy endureth for ever:', 0, 69, 'theology', 'Divine Heritage and Mercy', 'This passage reflects the theological concept of God''s providence and His enduring mercy toward His people. Many scholars believe it highlights the importance of understanding heritage not merely as a physical inheritance but as a spiritual legacy rooted in God''s faithful promises, which persist through generations.', 'person.2.fill', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discusses God''s mercy in giving land to Israel."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 21, 21, 'kjv', 'gave their land for an heritage', 4, 35, 'greek', 'Heritage in Original Language', 'נחלה (nachalah, H5159) - inheritance, possession. This Hebrew term emphasizes the idea of a lasting possession that is passed down through generations. It reflects God’s intention for His people to have a place that signifies His enduring relationship with them.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H5159", "description": "Strong''s number for ''hereditary possession''."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 21, 21, 'kjv', 'for his mercy endureth for ever:', 37, 69, 'question', 'Understanding Divine Mercy', 'What does it mean for God''s mercy to endure forever in the context of His promises? How does this eternal aspect of mercy influence our understanding of God''s faithfulness in our own lives and the lives of those around us?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 22, 22, 'kjv', 'Even an heritage unto Israel his servant: for his mercy endureth for ever.', 0, 74, 'connection', 'Heritage Promised', 'This phrase connects with Deuteronomy 9:5, where God explicitly states that He gives the land as an inheritance to His people, emphasizing the divine promise of a homeland. Additionally, Joshua 1:2 highlights the transition of leadership and the fulfillment of this promise. These connections showcase God''s faithfulness in fulfilling His covenant with Israel, reinforcing the theme of mercy throughout the Psalms.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Deuteronomy 9:5", "description": "God''s promise of land inheritance to Israel"}, {"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Joshua 1:2", "description": "Transitioning leadership and fulfillment of God''s promises"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 22, 22, 'kjv', 'heritage', 8, 16, 'greek', 'Significance of Heritage', 'נחלה (nachalah, H5159) - inheritance, possession. This Hebrew term emphasizes the idea of a divinely appointed possession, underscoring that the land is not merely a gift but a sacred trust given to Israel as part of God''s covenant. Understanding this word deepens our appreciation for the significance of the Promised Land in Israel''s identity and relationship with God.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H5159", "description": "Strong''s number for ''inheritance''"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 22, 22, 'kjv', 'for his mercy endureth for ever.', 42, 74, 'theology', 'Enduring Mercy', 'This repeated phrase reflects the theological concept of God''s steadfast love (chesed) and His eternal nature. Many scholars believe that the refrain highlights the unchanging character of God, which serves as a foundation for Israel''s hope and assurance in His promises. Understanding this enduring mercy invites believers to trust in God’s unwavering faithfulness through all circumstances.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary on the Psalms", "description": "Insights on God''s enduring mercy"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 22, 22, 'kjv', 'Israel his servant', 22, 40, 'question', 'Identity and Service', 'What does it mean for Israel to be called ''His servant''? How does this identity shape the understanding of their role in God''s plan? Reflecting on this can lead to a deeper exploration of the responsibilities and privileges that come with serving God, both in the historical context and in our personal lives today.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 23, 23, 'kjv', 'Who remembered us in our low estate', 0, 35, 'connection', 'Divine Remembrance', 'This phrase echoes the theme of God''s remembrance found in Exodus 2:24, where God hears the groaning of His people in bondage. It highlights God''s active engagement in human suffering and His faithfulness to deliver. Such remembrance is not passive but leads to action—demonstrating God''s commitment to His covenant people.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Exodus 2:24", "description": "God''s remembrance of Israel''s suffering"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 23, 23, 'kjv', 'in our low estate', 18, 35, 'theology', 'Human Humility', 'This passage suggests a doctrinal understanding of human humility and dependence on God. Many scholars believe that acknowledging our low estate is essential for experiencing God''s mercy. It serves as a reminder that God''s grace is most evident in our weakness, aligning with 2 Corinthians 12:9, where Paul states that God''s strength is made perfect in weakness.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "2 Corinthians 12:9", "description": "God''s strength in our weakness"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 23, 23, 'kjv', 'for his mercy endureth for ever', 37, 68, 'question', 'Enduring Mercy Reflection', 'How does the concept of God''s enduring mercy shape your understanding of His character? In what ways can recognizing this everlasting mercy influence how you extend grace to others? Consider the implications of mercy that does not fail, especially in relationships and personal challenges.', 'heart.text.square', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 23, 23, 'kjv', 'Who remembered us', 0, 17, 'greek', 'Greek Insight', 'זָכַר (zakar, H2142) - to remember, to mention. This Hebrew term signifies not just a mental acknowledgment but an active commitment to act on behalf of those remembered. It emphasizes the relational aspect of God''s remembrance, indicating His readiness to intervene in our lives.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H2142", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew term ''remember''"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 24, 24, 'kjv', 'And hath redeemed us from our enemies: for his mercy endureth for ever.', 0, 71, 'connection', 'Redemption Themes', 'This verse echoes the theme found in Exodus 6:6, where God promises to redeem His people from bondage in Egypt. Both passages highlight God''s active role in delivering His people. Understanding this connection emphasizes God''s unwavering commitment to His covenant and the overarching narrative of deliverance throughout Scripture.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Exodus 6:6", "description": "God''s promise of redemption to Israel"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 24, 24, 'kjv', 'redeemed', 9, 17, 'greek', 'Significance of Redemption', 'גָּאַל (ga''al, H1350) - to redeem, deliver, or rescue. This Hebrew word implies not only a financial transaction but also a deep relational restoration. It highlights God''s intervention in human affairs, signifying His desire to restore His people to Himself and to freedom.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H1350", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew term ''redeem''"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 24, 24, 'kjv', 'for his mercy endureth for ever.', 39, 71, 'theology', 'God''s Eternal Mercy', 'Many scholars believe that this phrase encapsulates the essence of God''s covenant faithfulness. The repetition of God''s mercy enduring forever throughout Psalm 136 reinforces the idea that His love and grace are unchanging and everlasting, serving as a foundation for our trust in Him across generations.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Insight on God''s enduring mercy"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 24, 24, 'kjv', 'redeemed us from our enemies', 9, 37, 'question', 'Understanding Our Enemies', 'In what ways does recognizing that God has redeemed us from our enemies transform our understanding of spiritual warfare today? How can this realization encourage us to rely on His strength and mercy in facing our own struggles?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 25, 25, 'kjv', 'Who giveth food to all flesh: for his mercy endureth for ever.', 0, 62, 'connection', 'Provision in Scripture', 'This verse resonates with Matthew 6:26, where Jesus reminds us that God feeds the birds of the air, highlighting His care for all creation. Additionally, in Philippians 4:19, Paul assures that God will supply all our needs. These connections emphasize God''s providential care and continuous mercy towards all living things, reinforcing the theme of divine sustenance.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Matthew 6:26", "description": "Jesus speaks of God''s provision for creation."}, {"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Philippians 4:19", "description": "Paul assures God''s provision for our needs."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 25, 25, 'kjv', 'giveth food to all flesh', 4, 28, 'theology', 'God''s Sustaining Grace', 'The phrase suggests a theological understanding of God as the ultimate provider, emphasizing His grace in sustaining life. Many scholars believe this reflects the broader biblical narrative of God''s care for His creation, as seen in the Israelites'' manna in the wilderness (Exodus 16). This provision is not only physical but also spiritual, illustrating God''s mercy that endures through all circumstances.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Exodus 16", "description": "God''s provision of manna for the Israelites."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 25, 25, 'kjv', 'for his mercy endureth for ever', 30, 61, 'question', 'Enduring Mercy Reflection', 'What does it mean for God''s mercy to endure forever in your life? How can you actively recognize and respond to His ongoing provision and grace? Reflecting on this can deepen your appreciation for His continuous support and influence in your daily experiences.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini');